    <title>Combined summary - Deanonymisation of clients in Bitcoin P2P network paper</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T14:25:02.795307+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-December/006967.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The use of Tor in Bitcoin transactions has been a topic of discussion due to its potential risks. While some argue that users abandon their privacy when directly connecting to the Bitcoin network, there are still attack vectors that make use of the DoS protection deficiencies when running Tor-only. The concern over users being forced off of Tor via DOS attacks is not alarming since it would be a conscious choice for users who decide to abandon their privacy. However, as Bitcoin's success and growth are expected in the future, very few users will make decisions regarding their privacy, so automated fallback or control over exits would be a concern.To achieve more synergy between Bitcoin users of varying skill levels, there should be a cleaner separation between technical mechanisms and policies suitable for users without technical skills. Core development can provide mechanisms to handle attacks specific to the Tor/Bitcoin combination. Distributors of consumer wallets can use this research to distribute their wallet with policies less prone to Tor-specific attacks. Tying Bitcoin to Tor too deeply does not seem like a good idea since most apps don't need onion routing, and Tor is large, complicated, and could be a liability in the future. Although there are limitations when using Bitcoin with Tor, both projects may need to evolve to better interface with each other. The author advocates for finding ways to improve the interoperability between Tor and Bitcoin while maintaining their standalone functionality.The conversation among Bitcoin developers and users revolves around the effectiveness of connecting to Bitcoin using Tor and the issues related to deanonymization of transactions from non-Tor connected hosts. While some suggest there is still room for improvement in DoS handling, others point out that Tor limitations are not the only concern and that users have a choice to abandon privacy or not use Bitcoin at all. The discussion also touches upon splitting communication between Tor and non-Tor for transaction submission and P2P networking and transaction relay, and the need to ensure hosts can continually use Tor or similar systems. Additionally, the conversation addresses a paper discussing fingerprinting approaches that probabilistically connect transactions to hosts whose IPs are already known and the need to address these issues in Bitcoin proper.The research paper from the Laboratory of Algorithmics, Cryptology and Security at the University of Luxembourg discusses the potential risks of obtaining IP addresses of clients involved in transactions on the core Bitcoin network. While Tor may be a first thought to mitigate this risk, Bitcoin over Tor has its own problems that prevent it from being effective. Researchers have found that Bitcoin does not protect user's IP address and it can be linked to the user's transactions in real-time. Transactions made during one session, even those made via unrelated pseudonyms, can be linked together, revealing up to 60% of the IP addresses behind the transactions made over the Bitcoin network. The author argues that it is important to prioritize the continual use of Tor or similar systems in order to protect hosts' privacy.Overall, while the severity of the Tor/Bitcoin issue has been acknowledged, it should not be considered a complete solution to privacy concerns. The use of Tor to improve wallet security is explored. While there are limitations when using Bitcoin with Tor, the two projects may need to evolve to better interface with each other. There is a suggestion for a cleaner separation between technical mechanisms and policies suitable for users without technical skills. Distributors of consumer wallets can use research to distribute wallets with policies less prone to attacks, especially for mainstream users. The effectiveness of connecting to Bitcoin using Tor has been measured, and there is still room for improvement in DoS handling. The level of anonymity in the Bitcoin network is addressed, with researchers finding that Bitcoin does not protect user's IP addresses and transactions can be linked together, revealing up to 60% of the IP addresses behind the transactions made over the Bitcoin network. Overall, it is suggested that improvements be made to interoperability between Tor and Bitcoin while maintaining their standalone functionality.</summary>
